  "lesson_groups": [
    {
      "key": "lessonGroup-2",
      "user_facing": true,
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "display_name": "Who's Looking at Your Digital Footprint?"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "digital-literacy-common-sense-media-2025"
      }
    }
  ],
  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "lesson-1",
      "name": "What You Send in \"That Moment When...\"",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can we act with empathy and positivity when we're online?**\n\nWe've all faced thorny situations where what we say or do could potentially harm or hurt someone. Being honest is important, but is there such a thing as being too honest? Sometimes, innocent -- but insensitive -- comments or actions can easily escalate to digital drama or even cyberbullying. Help students recognize and navigate these types of situations that happen online.",
        "student_overview": "**How can we act with empathy and positivity when we're online?**\n\nWe've all faced thorny situations where what we say or do could potentially harm or hurt someone. Being honest is important, but is there such a thing as being too honest? Sometimes, innocent -- but insensitive -- comments or actions can easily escalate to digital drama or even cyberbullying. Help students recognize and navigate these types of situations that happen online."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-1",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "digital-literacy-common-sense-media-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-2",
      "name": "Clicks for Cash",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How does internet advertising contribute to the spread of disinformation?**\n\nWell-crafted headlines benefit everyone. They help readers digest information and publishers sell news stories. But what if the headline is misleading? What if it's crafted just to get clicks or even to spread disinformation? \"Clickbait\" headlines may benefit advertisers and publishers, but they don't benefit readers. Help students recognize and analyze clickbait when they see it.",
        "student_overview": "**How does internet advertising contribute to the spread of disinformation?**\n\nWell-crafted headlines benefit everyone. They help readers digest information and publishers sell news stories. But what if the headline is misleading? What if it's crafted just to get clicks or even to spread disinformation? \"Clickbait\" headlines may benefit advertisers and publishers, but they don't benefit readers. Help students recognize and analyze clickbait when they see it."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-2",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "digital-literacy-common-sense-media-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-3",
      "name": "Risk Check for New Tech",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What privacy risks do new technologies present, and how do we decide if they're worth it?**\n\nNew tech, like location services and smart devices, helps make our lives easier and opens opportunities that didn't exist before. But these innovations also come with a cost -- especially to our privacy. Help students consider the benefits and drawbacks of these new technologies -- and decide whether they're ultimately worth it.",
        "student_overview": "**What privacy risks do new technologies present, and how do we decide if they're worth it?**\n\nNew tech, like location services and smart devices, helps make our lives easier and opens opportunities that didn't exist before. But these innovations also come with a cost -- especially to our privacy. Help students consider the benefits and drawbacks of these new technologies -- and decide whether they're ultimately worth it."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-3",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "digital-literacy-common-sense-media-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-4",
      "name": "Who's Looking at Your Digital Footprint?",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can information you post online affect your future opportunities?**\n\nOur digital footprints can have a powerful impact on our future. This can be a scary thought, given that what's in our digital footprint isn't always in our control. Teach students that digital footprints are an opportunity to showcase their best selves and craft a footprint that leads to future success.",
        "preparation": "- Use the Resource Notes on the [r _key_future_tracks/idaho-digital-literacy/2025] to review the resources beforehand.",
        "student_overview": "**How can information you post online affect your future opportunities?**\n\nOur digital footprints can have a powerful impact on our future. This can be a scary thought, given that what's in our digital footprint isn't always in our control. Teach students that digital footprints are an opportunity to showcase their best selves and craft a footprint that leads to future success."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-4",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "digital-literacy-common-sense-media-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-5",
      "name": "The Big Data Dilemma",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What are the benefits and drawbacks of online tracking?**\n\nMany of us are aware that we're being tracked when we go online. It's one of the ways our favorite websites and apps know how to recommend content just for us. But how much information are companies actually collecting? And what are they doing with it? Digging into the details can help us make smart decisions about our online privacy and how to protect it.",
        "preparation": "Use the Resource Notes on the [r _key_both_sides_of_the_track/idaho-digital-literacy/2025] to review the resources beforehand. ",
        "student_overview": "**What are the benefits and drawbacks of online tracking?**\n\nMany of us are aware that we're being tracked when we go online. It's one of the ways our favorite websites and apps know how to recommend content just for us. But how much information are companies actually collecting? And what are they doing with it? Digging into the details can help us make smart decisions about our online privacy and how to protect it."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-5",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "digital-literacy-common-sense-media-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-6",
      "name": "Hoaxes and Fakes",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can you avoid being fooled by fake videos and other information online?**\n\nWe know not to believe everything we hear, but what about what we see? Advancements in computer-generated graphics, facial recognition, and video production have led to a world of viral videos that are often difficult to identify as fake. Help your students learn to read what they see on the web \"laterally\" by showing them how to get off the page, check credibility, and find corroboration.",
        "preparation": "\n- This lesson is an introduction to lateral reading for your students.  For more information on lateral reading, we recommend these resources:\n\n  - [Lateral Reading: Reading Less and Learning More When Evaluating Digital Information.](https://poseidon01.ssrn.com/delivery.php?ID=840017005024119072096097108124115069035015009020000075110100091096006021074122003010028032100126054048009107103117082077123080055044090011064099015014120122094073026090054017013011117012070109013001005086113001104120108105096077121107014010025085016104&EXT=pdf) Sam Wineberg & Sarah McGrew, Stanford History Education Group, Sept 2017\n\n  - [Want to Be a Better Online Sleuth? Learn to Read Webpages Like a Fact-Checker.](https://www.poynter.org/fact-checking/2017/want-to-be-a-better-online-sleuth-learn-to-read-webpages-like-a-fact-checker/) Daniel Funke, Poynter, 10/16/2017\n\n  - [Web Literacy for Fact-Checkers - Four Moves.](https://webliteracy.pressbooks.com/chapter/four-strategies/) Mike Caulfield (Washington State University), 2017\n\n- This lesson includes several YouTube videos. You will need to confirm that they are accessible for students and not blocked by your school or district's filter. If they are blocked, you may want to show them whole-class using a projector or look for alternate resources.",
        "student_overview": "**How can you avoid being fooled by fake videos and other information online?**\n\nWe know not to believe everything we hear, but what about what we see? Advancements in computer-generated graphics, facial recognition, and video production have led to a world of viral videos that are often difficult to identify as fake. Help your students learn to read what they see on the web \"laterally\" by showing them how to get off the page, check credibility, and find corroboration."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-6",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "digital-literacy-common-sense-media-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 11: Intellectual Property",
      "name": "Intellectual Property",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "Students are asked to reflect on who owns their creative works from this class, such as their pixel images, before reading an article describing how ownership can become complicated as analog works become digital artifacts. After reading the article, students watch several videos explaining copyright and introducing them to the Creative Commons. Students then re-read the article answering three questions about the benefits, harms, and impacts of current copyright policy. Students use their new understanding of copyright to form an opinion about current copyright policies and create a small poster justifying their opinion with a quote from the article. This lesson is also a scaffold to the larger project that begins after this lesson which includes several tasks that are also a part of this lesson such as, annotating an article, answering questions, and forming an opinion using the article as evidence.",
        "preparation": "\n* Print out [r article_-_fortnite_stealing_dance_moves/idaho-digital-literacy/2025] with highlighters ready to mark the text. If you are unable to print copies, see the Teaching Tip below.\n- Check the [\"Teacher's Lounge\"](https://forum.code.org/t/resource-hub-digital-information-lessons-1-11/36468) forum for verified teachers to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers\n- If you are teaching virtually, consider checking our [Virtual Lesson Modifications](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1VqeD3PZyFnUXeUFjbY-z-fkz0XWmy5AqdXk-kRpgQzs/edit?usp=sharing)",
        "student_overview": "Learn about how people can own digital information and the ways they can share access to their creative digital works.",
        "unplugged": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 11: Intellectual Property",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "digital-literacy-common-sense-media-2025"
      }
    }
  ],
